  "prompt": "What is the meaning of Hanuman Chalisa?",
  "response": "The Hanuman Chalisa is a devotional hymn dedicated to Lord Hanuman, who is a significant deity in Hinduism known for his strength, devotion, and courage. Composed by the poet Tulsidas in the 16th century, this 40-verse poem praises Hanuman and recounts his virtues and exploits, particularly his role in the epic Ramayana as a devoted servant of Lord Rama.\n\nThe term \"Chalisa\" comes from the word \"chalis,\" which means forty in Hindi, indicating that the composition consists of forty verses. The Hanuman Chalisa is recited by devotees to seek strength, protection, and guidance, and it is believed to help overcome obstacles and difficulties. The text emphasizes the qualities of devotion, humility, and service, encouraging devotees to embody these virtues in their own lives. \n\nReciting the Hanuman Chalisa is considered a spiritual practice that can bring peace, reduce anxiety, and enhance one's faith in divine support.",
